Next, we quantified the precision of our estimate of the mean using bootstrapping to simulate the sampling distribution of the sample mean. Recall that sampling distributions are a specific kind of distribution: distributions of point estimates/sample statistics based on samples of size \(n\) used to estimate an unknown population parameter. Here is the code used:

set.seed(1701)
mh_means500 <- male_heights %>% 
  specify(response = HTM4) %>% 
  generate(reps = 500, type = "bootstrap") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "mean")

mh_means <- mh_means500 # Or whatever number of reps your memory allowed

Bootstrapping the sampling distribution helps us describe how values of the sample mean of heights \(\widehat{\mu}\) will vary from sample to sample due to sampling variability and thus identify typical and atypical values of \(\widehat{\mu}\).

mh_means %>% 
  summarize(mean_of_means = mean(stat))
# A tibble: 1 x 1
  mean_of_means
          <dbl>
1       178.060
(percentile_ci1 <- mh_means %>% 
  get_ci())
# A tibble: 1 x 2
   `2.5%` `97.5%`
    <dbl>   <dbl>
1 178.027 178.092
mh_means %>% 
  visualize() +
  shade_confidence_interval(percentile_ci1)

In fact, we could use dplyr to count how many bootstrapped means fall outside of the 95% confidence interval (the green shaded region bounded by the two green lines).

Counting the number of bootstrapped means shows that we have \(13/500 = .026\) samples below the lower bound (~2.5%) CI (shaded below in red). #Note - this comes out to an even 2.5% if you use 1000 reps ;)

mh_means %>% 
  count(stat < pull(percentile_ci1[1]))
# A tibble: 2 x 2
  `stat < pull(percentile_ci1[1])`     n
  <lgl>                            <int>
1 FALSE                              487
2 TRUE                                13
mh_means %>% 
  visualize() +
  shade_p_value(pull(percentile_ci1[1]), direction = "less")

We also count \(13/500 = .026\) samples above the upper bound (~97.5%) CI.

mh_means %>% 
  count(stat > pull(percentile_ci1[2]))
# A tibble: 2 x 2
  `stat > pull(percentile_ci1[2])`     n
  <lgl>                            <int>
1 FALSE                              487
2 TRUE                                13
mh_means %>% 
  visualize() + 
  shade_p_value(pull(percentile_ci1[2]), direction = "greater")

So, our original sample mean was 178.06. We used bootstrapping to quantify the precision of that sample estimate. Finally, we used infer::get_ci(type = "percentile") to calculate the range of stats (here, sample means) that encompasses 95% of the bootstrapped samples- > 5% of our bootstrapped samples produce means that fall outside of this range.

  4. Sampling: How do you acquire the sample of size \(n\) observations? What is the sample size \(n\)?
  5. Point estimates/sample statistics: What is the summary statistic based on the sample of size \(n\) that estimates the unknown population parameter?
    • Hint: https://moderndive.com/8-confidence-intervals.html
  6. Representative sampling: Is the sample procedure representative? In other words, do you believe the resulting samples look like the population?
  7. Random sampling: Was the sampling random?
    • Follow-up question: if you took another sample using the exact same methods, do you think you would get the exact same sample statistic?

  9. What is the spread of this sampling distribution?

5 OKCupid sample

In this lab, youll use a second different sample to estimate the average height of US males. This sample was taken from male volunteer users of the dating website OKCupid living in the San Francisco area. Heights are self-reported in inches. Use the code provided to load the profiles from the okcupiddata R package. This code filters for all males, converts height to centimeters, drops missing values, and take a random sample of \(n\) = 45 observations.

library(okcupiddata)
set.seed(2018)
cupid <- profiles %>% 
  filter(sex == "m") %>%
  mutate(height = 2.54*height) %>% 
  drop_na(height) %>% 
  sample_n(45) %>% 
  select(height) %>% 
  remove_rownames()

6 Bootstrapping for hypothesis test

Follow along in ModernDive, Appendix B.2.4.

Using the OKCupid sample data described above, well use bootstrapping to evaluate the following competing hypotheses:

6.1 In words

  • Null hypothesis: The mean height for all US men is equal to 178.06 cm (as we found above)

  • Alternative hypothesis: The mean height for all US men is greater than 178.06 cm.

6.2 In symbols (with annotations)

  • \(H_0: \mu = \mu_{0}\), where \(\mu\) represents the mean height for all US men and \(\mu_0\) is 178.06.
  • \(H_A: \mu > 178.06\)

Think: if the population mean were 178.06, how surprised would I be to get a sample mean as or more extreme than the one I got?

6.3 The bootstrap approach

First step is to calculate the sample mean height using yourOkCupid sample.

(cupid_bar <- cupid %>% 
  summarize(stat = mean(height)))
      stat
1 180.7916

In order to see if the observed sample mean of 180.79 is statistically greater than \(\mu_0 = 178.06\), we need to account for the sample size. We also need to determine a process that replicates how the sample of size 45 was selected.

We can use the idea of bootstrapping to simulate the population from which the sample came and then generate samples from that simulated population to account for sampling variability. Recall how bootstrapping would apply in this context:

  1. Sample with replacement from our OKCupid sample of 45 men and repeat this process 1,000 times (try set.seed(2018)),
  2. Calculate the mean for each of the 1,000 bootstrap samples created in Step 1.,
  3. Combine all of these bootstrap statistics calculated in Step 2 into a boot_distn object, and
  4. Shift the center of this distribution over to the null value of 178.06. (This is needed since it will be centered at 180.79 via the process of bootstrapping.)
  5. Use this distribution to observe our \(p\)-value. Recall this is a right-tailed test so we will be looking for values that are greater than or equal to 180.79 for our \(p\)-value.

Hint: With 2018 as my seed, I got a p-value of 0.005 with 1000 reps; and a p-value of 0.0062 with 10,000 reps.

7 Bootstrapping for a confidence interval

Follow along in ModernDive, Appendix B.2.4.

  1. Create a confidence interval for the unknown population parameter \(\mu\) using our OKCupid sample data and bootstrapping.
    • Note that we dont need to shift this distribution since we want the center of our confidence interval to be our point estimate \(\bar{x}_{obs} = 180.79\).
  2. Is 178.06 contained in this confidence interval as a plausible value of \(\mu\) (the unknown population mean)?
  3. Is the entire interval larger than the single value of 178? (that is, are there multiple integer values for height that fall into this confidence interval?)
  4. Does this match with our hypothesis test results above, where we failed to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative (\(\mu > 178.06\))?
  5. Complete this sentence:

Assuming that this sample is representative of all males in the US, we are 95% confident that the true average height for males in the US is between - and - centimeters.

8 Two means (independent samples) (on your own)

Follow along with the ModernDive Chapter 9 and ModernDive Appendix B.5 (search for the section titled: Two means (independent samples)).

Use this kaggle dataset, and test whether there is a difference in mean heights between men on the OKCupid dating site, versus all our POTUSes. Use a randomization test, which is a resampling-based method also called a permutation test. From ModernDive:

We can use the idea of randomization testing (also known as permutation testing) to simulate the population from which the sample came (with two groups of different sizes) and then generate samples using shuffling from that simulated population to account for sampling variability.

pres <- read_csv(here::here("data", "president_heights_new.csv")) %>% 
  select(height = `height(cm)`)

cupid_pres <- cupid %>% 
  bind_rows(pres, .id = "sample") %>% 
  mutate(sample = as.factor(sample))
